    <fr:title text="Syntactic (inference) rule">Syntactic (inference) rule</fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter><html:p>
  The basic form of a rule that describes a subset of a set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is given by:
</html:p>
  
    
    <fr:resource hash="225f9e047389422216018fec845a65c6"><fr:resource-content><html:img src="/notes/225f9e047389422216018fec845a65c6.svg" /></fr:resource-content><fr:resource-source type="latex" part="preamble"><![CDATA[
     
    \usepackage{eulervm}
  \usepackage{mathtools}
  \usepackage[scaled=0.92]{inconsolata}
  \usepackage{mathpartir}
  \usepackage{centernot}
  \usepackage[cal=cm]{mathalpha} % force \mathcal to CM-style callig

  \newcommand{\cf}[1]{\texttt{#1}}

    ]]></fr:resource-source><fr:resource-source type="latex" part="body"><![CDATA[\begin {mathpar}
  \inferrule *{
    x_1 \\ \ldots  \\ x_n
  }{
    x
  }
\end {mathpar}]]></fr:resource-source></fr:resource>
  
<html:p>
  In plain English this can be read as: <html:em>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x_1]]></fr:tex> to {x_n} are elements of the subset I am defining, then so is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex></html:em>. Here the elements <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x_1]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x_n]]></fr:tex> are called the <html:em>premises</html:em> of the rule while <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> is called the <html:em>conclusion</html:em> of the rule.
</html:p><html:p>
  One potentially helpful perspective for the set theoretic is that the conclusion <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> can be thought of as a label for the set of premises <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{x_1, \ldots , x_n\}]]></fr:tex></html:p></fr:mainmatter>
